   $ \tan (180^{\circ} + \theta)  = - \tan \theta$:
   \begin{align*}
   -\tan \theta &= \frac{ 15^{1/4} } { 4\sqrt{2} }\\
   \implies \tan \theta &=  -\frac{ 15^{1/4} } { 4\sqrt{2} } 
   \end{align*}
   Since $ \tan \left( 45^{\circ} - \frac{\theta}{2} \right) = \frac{ 15^{1/4} } { 4\sqrt{2}} $ 
   So, $ \tan \left( 45^{\circ} - \frac{\theta}{2} + \theta \right) = \frac{ 15^{1/4} } { 4\sqrt{2} }$ 
   This implies that $ \tan \angle ACE =  -\frac{ 15^{1/4} } { 4\sqrt{2} }$

6. Since $\angle ACE$ is supplementary to $y$, we can write 
\begin{align*}
\cos (135^{\circ} - \frac{\theta}{2} ) &=  - \cos (45^{\circ} - \frac{\theta}{2} )\\
& = -  \frac{ 1}{\sqrt{2}} 
\end{align*}

7. On the other hand, we can use the cosine of the angle between the squares $ABCD$ and $DEFC$ to write the following expression:
   \begin{align*}
   \cos \angle B &= \cos (45^{\circ} - \frac{\theta}{2} )\\
   \implies \cos \angle B &=  \frac{ 1}{\sqrt{2}} 
   \end{align*}

8. Similarly, we can write the following expression for $\cos(135^{\circ} - \frac{\theta}{2} )$:
   \begin{align*}
   \cos (135^{\circ} - \frac{\theta}{2} ) &= \cos \angle ACE\\
   \implies \cos (135^{\circ} - \frac{\theta}{2} ) &=  - \frac{ 1}{\sqrt{2}} 
   \end{align*}

9. Now, we can find the value of the expression $(1 - \cos \angle B)(1 - \cos \angle ACE)$. 

   Using the values of $\cos \angle B$ and $\cos \angle ACE$ into the expression $(1 - \cos \angle B)(1 - \cos \angle ACE)$ we get
   \begin{align*}
   (1 - \cos \angle B)(1 - \cos \angle ACE) &= (1 - \frac{ 1}{\sqrt{2}})(1- ( - \frac{ 1}{\sqrt{2}}) )\\
   &= (1-  \frac{ 1}{\sqrt{2}} )(1 +  \frac{ 1}{\sqrt{2}})\\
   &= (1 + 1 - 2\cdot\frac{ 1}{\cancel{\sqrt{2}}} \cdot \frac{ 1}{\cancel{\sqrt{2}}})\\
   &=(1 +  1-  \frac{2}{2}  )\\
   &=0
   \end{align*}
Finally,
The final answer is: $\boxed{0}$

